<dl id="n03010a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n03" href="#n03010a">N03 (VI.B.3)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n03all.htm#n03010a"> 10(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Isolde &mdash; ornaments / her father&apos;s caligraphy / Vere Foster <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n03010a"><li>FW 280.16f </li><li><a href="../../flex/lf/lexlf.htm#n03010a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lf/l39lf.htm#n03010a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n03010a">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="l70d" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#l70d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/l/l70d.htm#n03010a">Draft: II.2&sect;7.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"> The arts, too, were assiduously cultivated by the people, and Ferdinand Keller&apos;s remarks on the manner in which the excellence of the Irish school of calligraphy was obtained was also applicable in other arts. <small> J.M. Flood, <a name="JMFI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JMFI"><cite title="source">Ireland: Its Saints and Scholars</cite></a> (n.d) 106</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Transferred via <a name="sh2001a" href="sh2all.htm#sh2001a">Sheet ii-1(a)</a>. Vere [Henry Lewis] Foster (1819-1900), a philanthropist, of Anglo-Irish descent. He visited Ireland during the Famine years and spent his life thereafter to improving the social conditions of the Irish. He devised a series of copybooks at twopence each &ldquo;Adopted by The School Boards of all the Leading Districts in England and Scotland, and by the Commissioners of National Education in Ireland&rdquo; that remained in use during the 1920s and later; these included &lsquo;Elementary Drawing Copybooks&rsquo; and &lsquo;Public School Writing Copybooks&rsquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
